<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1913-10-08T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1913-10-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="1358" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1358">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 817.51/578.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Minister for Foreign
                                    Affairs</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-10-08">
                                    <hi rend="italic">October 8, 1913</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>I have the honor, in behalf of the Secretary of State, who is at the
                            moment absent from Washington, to request you to assure His <pb facs="1162" n="1058" xml:id="pg_1058"/> Excellency the President of
                            Nicaragua of our appreciation of the sentiments conveyed in your
                            telegram received October 7, the contents of which will be brought to
                            the knowledge of the Secretary.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">J. B. Moore</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>